==In popular culture==

===Media adaptations===
The battle was the subject of the 1969 film ''[[Battle of Britain (film)|Battle of Britain]]''. The cast included [[Laurence Olivier]] as [[Hugh Dowding]] and [[Trevor Howard]] as [[Keith Park]].<ref name="BOBFilm">[https://www.bbc.co.uk/films/2004/05/19/battle_of_britain_SE_1969_dvd_review.shtml Battle of Britain: Special Edition DVD (1969)] BBC. Retrieved: 22 December 2011</ref> It also starred [[Michael Caine]], [[Christopher Plummer]] and [[Robert Shaw (actor)|Robert Shaw]] as Squadron Leaders.<ref name="BOBFilm"/> Former participants of the battle served as technical advisers including [[Douglas Bader]], [[Adolf Galland]] and Hugh Dowding. An Italian film around the same time entitled ''[[Eagles Over London]]'' (1969) also featured the Battle of Britain. The 1988 ITV mini-series [[Piece of Cake (TV series)|''Piece of Cake'']], an aerial drama about a fictional Second World War RAF fighter squadron in 1940, features the battle. The [[Czech Republic|Czech]] film ''[[Dark Blue World]]'' (2001) also featured the battle, focusing on the Czech pilots who fought in the battle. In the 2001 movie, ''[[Pearl Harbor (film)|Pearl Harbor]]'', American participation in the Battle of Britain was exaggerated.{{citation needed|date=June 2017}} {{As of|2003}}, a Hollywood film named ''The Few'' was in preparation for release in 2008, based on the story of real-life US pilot [[Billy Fiske]], who ignored his country's neutrality rules and volunteered for the RAF. A ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' magazine outline of the film's historical content<ref>Fleming, Michael. [https://archive.today/20130205130141/http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117892183.html?categoryid=13&cs=1&query=billy+fiske "New flight plan for Cruise."] ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', 9 September 2003. Retrieved: 28 December 2007.</ref> was said in ''[[The Independent]]'' to have been described by Bill Bond, who conceived the [[Battle of Britain Monument in London]], as "Totally wrong. The whole bloody lot."<ref>Moreton, Cole. [http://arts.independent.co.uk/film/news/article55566.ece "Hollywood updates history of Battle of Britain: Tom Cruise won it all on his own."] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071218173843/http://arts.independent.co.uk/film/news/article55566.ece |date=18 December 2007 }} ''[[The Independent]]'', 11 April 2004. Retrieved: 28 December 2007.</ref> The 2018 film ''[[Hurricane (2018 film)|Hurricane: 303 Squadron]]'' depicts the contribution of Polish and Czech pilots to the campaign. The battle is also depicted in the 1956 film ''[[Reach for the Sky]]'' and ''First Light'' (BBC drama 2010).<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b00ttjz0 "First Light".] ''BBC'', 2010. Retrieved: 7 March 2014.</ref> In 2010, actor [[Julian Glover]] played a 101-year-old Polish veteran RAF pilot in the short film ''Battle for Britain''.<ref>[https://www.economist.com/blogs/easternapproaches/2010/09/battle_britain_1 "Dreaming Spires."] ''The Economist'' via ''economist.com,'' 16 September 2010. Retrieved: 29 September 2010.</ref>

It has also been the subject of many documentaries, including the 1941 [[Allied propaganda film]] ''[[Churchill's Island]]'', winner of the first [[Academy Award for Documentary Short Subject]].<ref name="NFB">[http://www.nfb.ca/playlist/its-oscar-time/viewing/Churchills_Island/ "Churchill's Island."] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090221182520/http://nfb.ca/playlist/its-oscar-time/viewing/Churchills_Island/ |date=21 February 2009 }} ''NFB.ca'', National Film Board of Canada. Retrieved: 17 February 2009.</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Campion|2015|pp=103–104}}</ref>
There was also the 1943 ''[[The Battle of Britain]]'' in [[Frank Capra]]'s ''[[Why We Fight]]'' series. It was included in an episode of 2004 BBC [[television documentary]] series ''[[Battlefield Britain]]''.

